  "why": "While DeepXplore explicitly enforces domain‐specific constraints such as clipping pixel values to the [0,255] range and adding only realistic lighting or occlusion effects, it does not clearly describe rounding the in‐memory floating‐point pixel values back to integers prior to serialization. The paper only mentions rounding gradients for generic “discrete features” (e.g., manifest flags in Android apps), and does not state that image pixel values—which are inherently discrete—are rounded after each update. Without an explicit rounding step, small fractional perturbations introduced in memory could be lost during standard image serialization, preventing reliable reproduction of the failures in practice. Thus, DeepXplore partially addresses format constraints (clipping and spatial masking) but omits the critical rounding step for image inputs.",
  "evidence": "Page 6 (§3 Overview): “We further add domain‐specific constraints (e.g., ensure the pixel values are integers within 0 and 255 for image input)…”\n\nPage 7 (§4.2 Domain‐specific constraints): “For example, for a generated test image x the pixel values must be within a certain range (e.g., 0 to 255). … Our algorithm ensures this property by modifying the gradient δrad … such that xᵢ₊₁ = xᵢ + s·δrad still satisfies the constraints.”\n\nPage 7 (§4.2 Domain‐specific constraints): “For discrete features, we round the gradient to an integer. For DNNs handling visual input (e.g., images), we add different spatial restrictions…”  \n\n-- Nowhere does the paper explicitly state that image pixels are rounded to integer values after mutation, risking loss of fractional perturbations upon serialization."  
